  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/tryResourceClose.html
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/io/fileio.html

Store the address within a class, so that you can increment it accordingly.  
Subsequently, you can use a _toString_ to return the text representation.

```java
class Address {
    long value;

    Address(long value) {
        this.value = value;
    }

    void increment() {
        value++;
    }
    
    void increment(long amount) {
        value += amount;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        long value = this.value;
        StringBuilder string = new StringBuilder();
        for (int count = 0; count &lt; 4; count++) {
            if (count != 0) string.insert(0, &#39;.&#39;);
            string.insert(0, value &amp; 0xff);
            value &gt;&gt;= 8;
        }
        return string.toString();
    }
}
```

Here is an example usage.

```java
Address address = new Address(0x0100003f);
address.increment();
System.out.println(address);
```

